Stonks – Stock Simulator

Course: CSE 122
Author: Jaiveer Lalli
Date: 1-22-2026
TA: Yang Wu

Overview

Stonks is a command-line stock market simulator that allows users to buy and sell stocks, track their portfolio, and save or load portfolio data from files. 
Users interact with the program through a menu system and can view all available stocks and their current holdings.

Features

Buy stocks – Users can select a stock and enter a budget to purchase fractional shares.

Sell stocks – Users can sell any amount of stock they own.

Display portfolio – View current holdings and the number of shares for each stock.

Save portfolio – Save the current portfolio to a file for later use.

Load portfolio – Load a portfolio from a previously saved file.

Final portfolio value – When quitting, the program displays the total value of the portfolio.

How to Use

Run the program in a Java-enabled environment.

Enter the name of a stock file when prompted. The file should contain stock tickers and prices.

Use the menu to perform actions:

Menu: (B)uy, (Se)ll, (D)isplay, (S)ave, (Q)uit


Follow the prompts to buy/sell stocks, view your portfolio, or save/load files.

Enter Q to quit and see the total portfolio value.

Example
Enter stocks file name: stocks.txt

Welcome to the CSE 122 Stocks Simulator!
There are 3 stocks on the market:
AAPL: 175.0
GOOG: 135.0
TSLA: 210.0

Menu: (B)uy, (Se)ll, (D)isplay, (S)ave, (Q)uit
Enter your choice: B
Enter the stock ticker: AAPL
Enter your budget: 350
You successfully bought AAPL.

Menu: (B)uy, (Se)ll, (D)isplay, (S)ave, (Q)uit
Enter your choice: D

Portfolio:
AAPL 2.0

File Structure

Stonks.java – Main Java file containing all logic for stock management.

Stock data files – Plain text files with stock tickers and prices (one stock per line).

Notes

Program uses fractional shares for simplicity.

Requires proper formatting of stock files: each line should have a ticker and a numeric price.

All input is case-insensitive for stock tickers.
